[{"id": "416b83ac-1108-4694-ba1b-52c3e2a941bf", "chunk_index": 0, "text": "ASSISTANT: The Estimator's on site. Upload a photo of the job and tell me what you're planning. I'll tell you what materials you need, but I'm gonna have some questions about those dimensions first.\nUSER: customer wants new box type steps. current ones exend past railing. new ones won't \nASSISTANT: Alright, I see the job. Deck box steps, two risers down to grade, currently overhanging past the railing posts on both sides \u2014 particularly on the right where that bottom tread is sticking out a good bit. Customer wants them pulled back to fit flush within the railing line. Clean look. I get it.\n\n**A few things I'm noticing right off the bat:**\n1. **Stain is failing badly** \u2014 peeling all over, and I can see green PT lumber bleeding through. If the customer wants these to match the existing deck, that's a whole separate conversation about prep and restaining.\n2. **That bottom step on the right** looks like it might be sitting directly on the pavers with no real support underneath. I'd want to check that framing.\n3. **Railing posts** \u2014 I need to know if those are staying put or getting modified. The new steps will terminate at the inside face of those posts.\n\n**Before I can give you a material list, I need these measurements:**\n\n- **Width between railing posts** (inside face to inside face) \u2014 that's your new step width\n- **Total rise** from finished grade (top of those pavers) to the deck surface\n- **Current tread depth** on each step (front to back)\n- **Deck board thickness** \u2014 looks like 5/4 decking (Nominal) but confirm\n- **Are you reusing the existing step framing/stringers**, or tearing it all out and building new boxes from scratch?\n\nGet me those numbers and I'll have your cut list and material list ready to go. And tell the customer \u2014 if they want it to last, we're talking pressure-treated framing with either PT or composite treads. Their call.", 